The five accused will have to answer to 109 charges, including corruption and racketeering. CAPE TOWN - Former Western Cape police commissioner Arno Lamoer and his co-accused will go on trial for corruption next year. Lamoer, Darius van der Ross, Saleem Dawjee and Kolindren and Sharon Govender appeared in the Western Cape High Court for a pre-trial hearing today. The State and defence have indicated they are ready to proceed to trial. In March, the five accused will have to answer to 109 charges, including corruption and racketeering. The State claims Lamoer and three other former police officers received expensive gifts and cash amounting to over a million rand from businessman Saleem Dawjee in exchange for favours. WATCH: My family are in agony everyday - Lamoer